post_text: Happy Birthday and special thanks to Chris ‚ÄúLudacris‚Äù Bridges for his partnership with Fulton County Government to ensure that everyone is counted in the #2020Census. The deadline to complete the Census is September 30. Respond today at 2020census.gov or by calling 844-330-2020. The Ludacris Foundation U.S. Census Bureau
shared_text:
The Ludacris Foundation
Yesterday at 5:36 PM ¬∑

www.2020Census.gov

Today as we are celebrating the birthday of our Founder Chris @ludacris Bridges, we are pleased to announce that we have joined forces with Fulton County Government to help in spreading the word about the #2020Census here in ATL!

Atlanta has about 400,000 people that are uncounted. That means that just year one after the census 400,000 x $2,300 = $920 million dollar will not be allotted to communities in need. Most of the uncounted are in South Atlanta!

This means underfunded school, ranging from no free lunches to underfunded books and technology.

If just 10% of the 400,000 take 5 minutes to complete the census that would result in $920 million coming into the community! FILL YOURS OUT TODAY!!!

Atlanta has about 400,000 people that are uncounted. That means that just year one after the census 400,000 x $2,300 = $920 million dollar will not be allotted to communities in need. Most of the uncounted are in South Atlanta!

This means underfunded school, ranging from no free lunches to underfunded books and technology.

If just 10% of the 400,000 take 5 minutes to complete the census that would result in $920 million coming into the community! FILL YOURS OUT TODAY!!!

September is Library Card Sign Up Month! There is nothing more empowering or exciting than getting your own library card. Like this year‚Äôs library superhero, #WonderWoman, a library card can give you superpowers! It gives residents of all ages access to technology, resources and services to pursue your passions and dreams. From virtual storytimes to audiobooks to DIY classes, there is something for everyone.

This year, the Fulton County Library System wants you to go online and get your library card throughout the month of September and check out a book, movie or music using the library‚Äôs many digital resources maybe even place a book on hold and pick it up using curbside services. Visit www.fulcolibrary.org/digitallibrary to get started.

The Fulton County Youth Commission provides 500 toiletry packs to the non-profit organization Love Beyond Walls. The packs supplied were donated with items for men, women and children. Each pack included items such as toothpaste, toothbrushes, shower gels, anti-bacterial wipes, deodorant, shampoo, washcloths, and women‚Äôs hygiene items.

Additionally, all hygiene packs included a Youth Commission "HOPE Card," which features resources from internal and external partners offering health, shelter, rehabilitation, employment, and sexual exploitation prevention services.

The Career ReBoot Fulton program will significantly expand access to computer training and provide a stepping stone for thousands of Fulton County residents to improve their digital skills as they re-enter the workforce. The program will enable recently laid-off or unemployed workers to earn industry-recognized certifications either online or at one of Goodwill‚Äôs career training centers.

The Atlanta Regional Commission (ARC) has awarded Fulton County $767,047 as part of the CARES Act to ensure adequate nutrition for Fulton seniors. Since March, the County has provided 135,454 meals to seniors. With additional funds, the Department of Senior Services will deliver approximately 40,000 additional home delivered meals and 26,500 additional congregate meals now through May 31, 2021.

www.fultoncountyga.gov/news/2020/08/10/fulton-county-receives-cares-act-funds-to-ensure-adequate-nutrition-for-seniors

Today, Robb Pitts, Chairman, Board of Commissioners of Fulton County, County Manager Dick Anderson, and Fulton County Board of Health Director Dr. Lynn Paxton joined Governor Brian Kemp, U.S. Surgeon General Dr. Jerome Adams and officials from the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services in announcing the opening of the newest mega-testing site in Fulton County, at Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport.

This newest testing site brings testing capacity within Fulton County to more than 10,000 tests daily. Fulton County previously doubled testing capacity from June to July to 5,500 tests daily. By the end of 2020, more than 1 million COVID-19 tests will have been conducted within Fulton County.

https://fultoncountyga.gov/news/2020/08/10/fulton-county-on-track-for-1-million-covid-19-tests-in-2020

On August 5, the Fulton County Board of Commissioners voted to reduce its millage rate for the fifth consecutive year.

The approved 2020 General Fund millage rate of 9.776 mills represents a decrease from 9.899 mills in 2019, and is revenue neutral.

Fulton County has consistently reduced its millage rate while maintaining a strong credit rating and fund balance.

post_text: The Fulton County Jail is now fully accredited by the National Commission on Correctional Health Care (NCCHC). This announcement by the NCCHC states that the Fulton County Jail is 100 percent compliant with all applicable standards. The 39 standards cover the full scope of inmate health care. This means the Fulton County Jail is meeting the highest standards in health care for inmates which benefits the community as a whole. For more on this story, visit www.fultoncountyga.gov/news/2020/08/05/fulton-county-jail-earns-accreditation-in-health-care.

post_text:
COVID-19 is not only having a profound impact on parents, but it has also upended the lives of children yet they are rarely are included in national conversations. How are teens handling stress? Who is helping them navigate these difficult times? What do they need to cope and move forward? The Fulton County Department of Behavioral Health and Developmental Disabilities (BHDD) will host a "Community Conversation" with teens titled "Protecting the Mental Health of Our Future Leaders: Fulton Teens Speak Up during This Time of National Upheaval".

The Community Conversation begins at 1.p.m., tomorrow, July 21. The conversation can be viewed on the FGTV - Fulton Government Television at www.youtube.com/FultonGovernmentTV. Interested parents, adults or youth can submit questions by emailing social@fultoncountyga.gov.

For more information, please visit: https://www.fultoncountyga.gov/news/2020/07/07/teens-speak-up-during-this-time-of-national-upheaval.

post_text:
Last week the Secretary of State mailed absentee ballots to approximately 30,000 Fulton County voters who were on the list of voters who are eligible to receive absentee ballots for every election this year. We have learned of some voters in this group who received incorrect ballots.

Specifically, Fulton County identified more than 600 voters who voted on the Democratic ballot in June but were mailed nonpartisan ballots by the Secretary of State. We notified the Secretary of State‚Äôs office of this issue on Tuesday and requested that they take corrective action.

We have been advised that the Secretary of State‚Äôs office has mailed corrected ballots and instructions to all affected voters. Any voter who received a ballot different than the party for which they cast a ballot in June should hold their ballot until they receive the correct ballot.

post_text: Local media received a preview of the State Farm Arena set to be the largest-ever precinct in Georgia starting with early voting on July 20 for the Georgia General Primary Runoff Election on August 11. The tour led by Atlanta Hawks & State Farm Arena, CEO Steve Koonin, Robb Pitts, Chairman, Board of Commissioners of Fulton County, and Fulton County Registration & Elections Director Richard Barron previewed the precinct set-up and process for Fulton County voters. The State Farm Arena set to support social distancing and high volume turnout will house 100 voter machines with complimentary parking and direct transit access through MARTA. To learn more about the partnership, please visit: bit.ly/2ZBr7HG. #TrueToAtlanta #FultonVotes

post_text: On July 8, 2020, the Fulton County Commissioners voted to make Juneteenth a county holiday. #Juneteenth, traditionally observed on June 19 marks the end of slavery in the United States on June 9, 1865. Starting in 2021, Juneteenth will be added to the County holiday calendar. To learn more, please visit: www.fultoncountyga.gov/news/2020/07/13/fulton-county-board-of-commissioners--declares-juneteenth-a-county-holiday.

post_text:
COVID-19 is not only having a profound impact on parents, but it has also upended the lives of children yet they are rarely are included in national conversations. How are teens handling stress? Who is helping them navigate these difficult times? What do they need to cope and move forward? The Fulton County Department of Behavioral Health and Developmental Disabilities (BHDD) will host a "Community Conversation" with teens titled "Protecting the Mental Health of Our Future Leaders: Fulton Teens Speak Up during This Time of National Upheaval".

The Community Conversation begins at 1.p.m. July 21, 2020. The conversation can be viewed on the FGTV - Fulton Government Television at www.youtube.com/FultonGovernmentTV. Interested parents, adults or youth can submit questions by emailing social@fultoncountyga.gov.

For more information, please visit: www.fultoncountyga.gov/news/2020/07/07/teens-speak-up-during-this-time-of-national-upheaval.

Louis Delsarte was honored with a proclamation Wednesday proclaiming Saturday, May 2, 2020, as ‚ÄúLouis J. Delsarte Remembrance Day‚Äù in Fulton County. The Board of Commissioners applauds the many artistic contributions of Louis Delsarte to the art world and to the local community.

Delsarte has completed large public murals in Brooklyn, Harlem, and the largest in Atlanta; the 129 foot long Martin Luther, Jr. Memorial Mural, dedicated in 2010 at the Peace Plaza on Auburn Avenue near Dr. King‚Äôs birthplace. Delsarte‚Äôs wife is pictured.

Fulton County voters can cast their ballots for the August 11 General Primary, Nonpartisan, and Special Election Runoff election starting Monday, July 20.

In total, Fulton County will offer 20 early voting locations, including Georgia‚Äôs largest voting location at State Farm Arena. Early Voting will take place weekdays from Monday, July 20 through Friday, August 7 from 8:30 a.m. to 6 p.m., Saturday, July 25, and Saturday, August 1 from 8:30 a.m. to 6 p.m.

Locations are distributed throughout Fulton County, and any voter registered in Fulton County may vote at any Fulton County polling location. At least three sites are located in each Fulton County commission district.

For more information, please visit: www.fultoncountyga.gov/news/2020/07/08/fulton-county-announces-early-voting-locations.

All Probate Court offices (Downtown, North Service Center, and South Service Center) have resumed normal office hours.

All locations have resumed the acceptance of Weapons Carry License Applications and Applications for Renewal of Weapons Carry Licenses. Be advised that the Court expects to receive a large number of applications over the next several months and significant delays should be expected at each location. If you may wish to complete your application before coming to the Probate Court, the form for applying for the Weapons Carry License is now available on our website. The availability of the form will help limit the time customers spend in our physical office.

Governor Kemp signed an Executive Order on May 8, 2020, extending the time for applying for a renewal. You are given an additional 120 days after the expiration date to apply for renewal if on the face of your license it expired between February 13, 2020, and June 12, 2020. To learn more, visit: fultoncountyga.gov/inside-fulton-county/fulton-county-departments/probate-court.

Stay safe and get your library materials with contact-free curbside pickup! The Fulton County Library System is now open for curbside pickup services and will allow patrons with library books and materials at home to begin returning those materials to their local library branches. County libraries will remain closed for typical in-branch library services, but items placed on hold by library patrons will be available for pickup from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m., Monday through Friday at designated library branches.

More details: http://afpls.org/news/2697-libraries-prepare-to-reopen-for-curbside-services-july-1.

post_text:
The Small Business Administration‚Äôs Paycheck Protection Program officially closes to new applications after today, June 30, which is the final day an application can be submitted to the SBA portal.

Changes made to the law on June 5, in the form of the Paycheck Protection Program Flexibility Act, expanded from eight to 24 weeks the period that businesses had to spend loan proceeds. The new law also increased the loan's portion that could go toward nonpayroll expenses from 25% to 40% and still be forgivable, making the program more attractive.

Recent SBA guidance also states that businesses must make their decision about the program as soon as possible. ‚ÄúSmall businesses that have yet to apply for and receive a PPP loan need to be informed of the terms of PPP loans as soon as possible,‚Äù the guidance reads.

For more information or to apply, go to: www.sba.gov/page/coronavirus-covid-19-small-business-guidance-loan-resources

post_text: We will celebrate the end of National Pollinator Week with a Pollinator Highlight ‚Äì the Ruby-Throated Hummingbird! Georgia is home to 11 hummingbird species throughout the year, with the ruby-throated hummingbird being the only species known to nest in Georgia. Hummingbirds often pick up pollen along their beak and feathers as they drink nectar from tubular flowers. Learn more about the hummingbirds in your backyard by visiting the Georgia Department of Natural Resources Wildlife Resources Division at georgiawildlife.com/hummingbirds-your-backyard.

June 22-28, 2020 is National Pollinator Week! This week, we celebrate the impact of pollinators on our daily life and discuss ways to protect them.

Kickoff National Pollinator Week by participating in the inaugural Pollinator Power Party, brought to you by the Electric Power Research Institute (EPRI). The week will be filled with fun, family friendly events to help you understand the life and purpose of pollinators. There will be cooking tutorials, science, art, music, gardening, and a LIVE stream of a new documentary film, all dedicated to pollinators. All events will take place virtually. Please register to attend by visiting https://cvent.me/E5b1DD. #powerinpollinators.

For more information on how you can participate in National Pollinator Week events, please contact Kelli Edwards at Kelli.Edwards@fultoncountyga.gov or Hannah Penn at Hannah.Penn@fultoncountyga.gov.

post_text:
The first Fulton Fresh Mobile Market session will run June 9 - July 9, 2020. The Fulton Fresh Mobile Market was created to educate residents living in communities designated as food deserts on the importance of fresh and in-season produce. This season, participants will take part in online nutrition education module and curbside pick-up instead of in-person activities.

Every week, attendees will participate in a 10 minute online UGA Extension Fulton County nutrition education module. On the day of the market, completion of the online module will be verified and participants are given a free bag of in-season produce from our mobile market to take home and prepare. Pick-up will be outdoors, contact-less, and curbside.

For more information on the Fulton Fresh Mobile Market, please visit: http://ow.ly/qss350A4epY.

post_text:
Remember that all absentee ballots must be received by the Department of Registration & Elections by 7 p.m. on Election Day. Thousands of voters have returned their absentee ballots, and we know many more are expected today and tomorrow.

To help ensure absentee ballots are received in time, Fulton County has installed 20 absentee ballot drop boxes. Ballots are picked up daily from these secure boxes. You can find the list of dropbox locations and a finder tool at this page: www.fultoncountyga.gov/absenteedropbox

Boxes will be locked at 7 p.m. tomorrow.

Please note: Georgia law does not allow absentee ballots to be turned in at a polling place. Voters who requested an absentee ballot and choose to vote in person will be asked to complete an affidavit at their polling place. If a voter has not received a requested absentee ballot, we ask that they vote at the polls if possible.

The Fulton County Board of Commissioners and Fulton County Schools have announced plans to expand partnership providing additional behavioral health counseling to students and their families in response to COVID-19.

This collaboration will add 20 new schools and 31 counselors. Expanded services include school-based in-person and virtual therapy for students. For more on this story, please visit: https://bit.ly/36AIZnV.
